i like this ... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=daareonravenstar>Daareon Ravenstar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/29/03 12:12 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Quad Kiting Locations Guide - Rough Draft</span><hr size=1> Two personal notes.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
Quading in Dawnshroud is viable until 44. Large Zelniaks and Wolves are still blue at this level. The odd large Zelniak (1/6) is light blue.  I was still getting 4-5% of a level at 44 here per quad.<br>
<br>
Zelniaks have 1300-1500hps. Wolves are in the 1600hp range. <br>
<br>
The drawback to this zone is the odd named (agro) Wolf/Zelniak and of course the lightcrawlers. While these arnt terribly threatening to a PC with SoW, they are quite disruptive to your rhythm and will agro regardless of level.  <br>
<br>
Dont expect any loot. There is no coin, and no items of consequence.<br>
<br>
At higher levels It would be possible to quad stonegrabbers, but they do hit hard and have a ton of hps. Not recommended as value for mana.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
Quading the beach in Gulf Of Gunthak<br>
Level 40-47.<br>
<br>
I wouldnt recomend it to inexperienced quaders for a number of reasons. <br>
<br>
1. The mobs seem to have a very random HP range. (1200hp-1500hp for the lower level skeletons, 1500-1800hps for some zombies, 1800-2400hps for the odd named mob). <br>
<br>
2. Snared mobs all move at different speeds depending on type. Zombies tend to be quite slow. Mixed quads can be difficult to keep bunched.<br>
<br>
3. All undead types will keep going for you, even at 1% health.<br>
<br>
4. The pathing is fairly good, but mobs do warp into melee range in some spots (left hand side of the beach has at least three spots I know of where this happens.). <br>
<br>
5. You usually have to clear a safe kiting lane initially, and then re-clear every 20 or so minutes. This may put you in competition with other players if you play during busy times.<br>
<br>
So your milage may vary. Solo XP is fairly good here, but I feel the beach is anti-quad by design.  The loot is appropriate (occasional peridots, opals, emeralds, black pearls, gold broaches) but doesnt approach hill giants.<br>
<br>
